WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:15.050
RAJIV SATYAL: I'm
Indian, just Indian.

00:00:15.050 --> 00:00:18.180
I'm not South Asian any more
than Russians are North Asian.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:20.850
I'm not Asian Indian
or East Indian.

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:22.630
There are 1.3 billion of us.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:24.550
We don't need a
cardinal direction, OK?

00:00:24.550 --> 00:00:27.120
It's not our fault that
Christopher Columbus got lost.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:30.640
Sure, we love our states, but
there's strength in numbers.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:33.670
One out of every six
human beings is Indian,

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:35.370
so stop dividing us.

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:37.940
The British already
did that once.

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:40.560
And we need to quit saying
that we're not Indian

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:44.410
because I wasn't born here, or
sound like this, or eat that.

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:46.800
Our hearts are Indian.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:47.880
We are feelers.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.340
We gave the world the
romance of Bollywood films

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:53.210
and the music of Ravi
Shankar and Zubin Mehta

00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:55.510
and Lata Mangeshkar
and Asha Bhosle

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:58.430
and the allure of
the "Kama Sutra."

00:00:58.430 --> 00:00:59.690
We are thinkers.

00:00:59.690 --> 00:01:02.300
We are great at math
because we invented numbers.

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:04.125
And we're pretty
good at letters too.

00:01:04.125 --> 00:01:06.810
We are doctors and
engineers and techies.

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.460
And we mean business.

00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:11.420
We're the world's third largest
economy and the wealthiest

00:01:11.420 --> 00:01:13.220
ethnic group in America.

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:15.320
We are huge and efficient.

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:16.924
India is all on one time zone.

00:01:16.924 --> 00:01:18.340
That way, everybody
in the country

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:20.890
is still late, but
at the same time.

00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:23.860
We never invade anyone because
we already have everything.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:26.770
Chess, the ruler, the button,
wireless communication,

00:01:26.770 --> 00:01:30.880
arranged marriage flush
toilets, steel, democracy-- all

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:32.780
us, all India.

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:34.830
And you are welcome,
world, for yoga,

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:37.480
and elevating cricket into
a multibillion-dollar sport,

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:39.950
and making food so good that
you sailed across the planet

00:01:39.950 --> 00:01:41.090
to come have some.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:42.620
Our food is hot.

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:44.130
Our country is hot.

00:01:44.130 --> 00:01:45.550
Our women are hot.

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:48.580
Our men are-- lucky.

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:51.430
Where the world
prays, we meditate.

00:01:51.430 --> 00:01:53.690
We practically invented
religious tolerance.

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:56.690
And we gave you Mahatma
Gandhi and pundits and gurus

00:01:56.690 --> 00:02:00.070
and karma and dharma and
kismet and reincarnation.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:02.170
The motherland is
magical and mystical.

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:04.570
And no matter who you are,
you can find yourself here,

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:09.480
in incredible India.
[SPEAKING HINDI]-- I am Indian.

00:02:09.480 --> 00:02:12.620
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:14.540
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:19.330
And I'm late.

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:21.880
Told you I was Indian.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:23.340
It's an honor to
be here at Google.

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:27.782
I actually got a degree
in materials engineering.

00:02:27.782 --> 00:02:28.740
That was the big thing.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:30.260
That's how I prepped for
comedy, I got a degree

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:31.540
in materials engineering.

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:33.309
I was going to
work in wafer fab.

00:02:33.309 --> 00:02:34.850
I was going to be
a wafer fabrication

00:02:34.850 --> 00:02:36.360
engineer in the Silicon Valley.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:40.619
And until today,
February 19, 2016,

00:02:40.619 --> 00:02:41.910
I have disappointed my parents.

00:02:41.910 --> 00:02:43.784
But today, I'm working
in the Silicon Valley.

00:02:43.784 --> 00:02:44.460
So here I am.

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:46.942
So I guess, finally,
my parents can be proud

00:02:46.942 --> 00:02:49.150
that I'm actually here in
the Silicon Valley with you

00:02:49.150 --> 00:02:51.830
like a good Indian.

00:02:51.830 --> 00:02:53.340
It's a lot of
Indians here today,

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:56.061
which is mostly--
token white guy.

00:02:56.061 --> 00:02:56.560
OK.

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:59.150
Right, in the front row--
it's still your country,

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:00.199
don't worry.

00:03:00.199 --> 00:03:00.740
That's great.

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:03.336
It still works out, so
no problem with that.

00:03:03.336 --> 00:03:04.710
No need to take
the country back.

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:07.150
OK.

00:03:07.150 --> 00:03:10.230
I'm actually giving TED X
talk in a couple of weeks.

00:03:10.230 --> 00:03:12.730
And so people have been asking
me-- friends, they're saying,

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:13.670
oh, you're speaking at Google.

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:14.961
You're giving a talk at Google.

00:03:14.961 --> 00:03:15.800
Are you practicing?

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:17.341
You don't come to
Google to practice.

00:03:17.341 --> 00:03:18.560
This is the Super Bowl, OK.

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:21.640
So this is the highlight
of my year so far,

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:24.160
but it's only, what, 50
days old, so not a problem.

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.600
But I'm here to give a
speech and break down

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:29.620
that video that you saw.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:31.760
How many people, by round of
applause, have seen that video?

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:32.670
How many people have seen it?

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:33.220
OK.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:33.820
You can clap.

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:34.319
It's OK.

00:03:34.319 --> 00:03:35.820
Let's get some
energy going in here.

00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:36.670
It's Friday.

00:03:36.670 --> 00:03:38.962
How many people have not seen
it, by round of applause?

00:03:38.962 --> 00:03:40.711
I guess it's a weird
thing to applaud for.

00:03:40.711 --> 00:03:41.650
But yeah, that's fine.

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:42.900
I'm glad that if
we hadn't seen it,

00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:44.274
we wish we wouldn't
have seen it.

00:03:44.274 --> 00:03:46.699
But no, I'm glad that a
lot of you had seen it.

00:03:46.699 --> 00:03:47.490
Some of you hadn't.

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:49.050
So that's very cool.

00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:52.730
But I'm going to explain,
I think, to some extent,

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:56.570
why that video worked, and also
tell you a little about humor,

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:58.204
about stand-up, about jokes.

00:03:58.204 --> 00:03:59.620
And I want to make
it interactive.

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:02.946
So if you have questions or if
you are bored-- well, if you're

00:04:02.946 --> 00:04:04.070
bored, just leave, I guess.

00:04:04.070 --> 00:04:05.570
But if you have
questions, just feel

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:07.870
free to put your hand up
or shout something out.

00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:10.036
I think that's always a
good thing to be able to do.

00:04:10.036 --> 00:04:12.420
It's odd, though, to talk
about why something worked

00:04:12.420 --> 00:04:14.850
as a stand-up comedian,
because normally, we

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:15.962
talk about our failures.

00:04:15.962 --> 00:04:17.670
We don't really talk
about our successes,

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:19.524
because failure is funny.

00:04:19.524 --> 00:04:20.190
You know I mean?

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:21.606
It's funny to watch
somebody fail.

00:04:21.606 --> 00:04:23.523
That's why we have fail
blogs and hashtag fail

00:04:23.523 --> 00:04:24.147
and everything.

00:04:24.147 --> 00:04:25.040
It's a lot funnier.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:26.240
If I just get up
here and tell you,

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:28.323
and that's how I got the
girl back to my apartment

00:04:28.323 --> 00:04:30.210
and I hooked up with
her, OK, [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:35.850
That's not really a funny story,
that's just somebody bragging.

00:04:35.850 --> 00:04:39.700
I do want to talk about jokes.

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:40.700
I do live in the Valley.

00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:42.699
And I don't know how many
people saw "Clueless."

00:04:42.699 --> 00:04:45.500
This movie's now 20 years old,
which is crazy for me to think.

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:46.450
Somebody's nodding back there.

00:04:46.450 --> 00:04:47.000
OK, good.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.092
So-- which is why, up here, I
have to speak like an adult,

00:04:52.092 --> 00:04:53.300
because I live in the Valley.

00:04:53.300 --> 00:04:56.190
Normally we tend to go up
at the end of our sentences.

00:04:56.190 --> 00:04:58.430
We all kind of talk
like this down in LA.

00:04:58.430 --> 00:05:00.430
And I know, in San
Francisco, you don't like LA.

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:01.804
So as long as I
make fun of LA, I

00:05:01.804 --> 00:05:04.230
think I'm going
to do pretty well.

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:07.110
But I realize that some of
my friends, they're cool.

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:08.680
I'm not a cool guy.

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:09.980
I've never been a cool guy.

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:13.182
Some of my friends, they'll
develop cool phrases.

00:05:13.182 --> 00:05:14.890
They'll say, yeah,
let's all turn up, yo.

00:05:14.890 --> 00:05:15.640
Let's all turn up.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:16.591
That's a good look.

00:05:16.591 --> 00:05:18.840
I want to talk like that,
but it just doesn't come out

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:19.690
of my mouth like that.

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:21.100
I always pick up the
annoying phrases.

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:22.349
I think she's already leaving.

00:05:22.349 --> 00:05:23.847
OK, fine.

00:05:23.847 --> 00:05:24.930
But I always pick them up.

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:26.554
Because a friend of
mine in the Valley,

00:05:26.554 --> 00:05:27.682
she always says, "right."

00:05:27.682 --> 00:05:29.140
She's one of these
women who always

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:30.880
says "right" at the
end of her sentences.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:35.160
Or whenever somebody gets
finished speaking, she'll go,

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:37.470
"anyway," which is
such a beautifully

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:40.030
condescending way of speaking.

00:05:40.030 --> 00:05:40.790
It's so great.

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:42.373
I mean, somebody
will say, "and that's

00:05:42.373 --> 00:05:44.890
why I'm voting for
Donald Trump"-- "anyway."

00:05:44.890 --> 00:05:46.680
It's just such a
great thing to say.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:48.680
It's amazing.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:51.020
But I noticed I had to stop
saying the word "like."

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:52.970
I was saying "like" constantly.

00:05:52.970 --> 00:05:54.710
And I realized I
had a problem when

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:56.260
I said it three times in a row.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:56.900
OK?

00:05:56.900 --> 00:06:00.430
So I actually said, "Like
like like?" as a question.

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:02.790
And some of you understand
that, which is sad.

00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:05.040
We have a problem-- it's an
epidemic in this country--

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:06.210
of likes, too many likes.

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:08.390
And I think I'm not at Facebook,
so I should stop saying "like."

00:06:08.390 --> 00:06:10.890
But the point being-- I think
you can like things on YouTube

00:06:10.890 --> 00:06:11.617
too, right?

00:06:11.617 --> 00:06:12.450
But I realized this.

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:13.770
Actually, on our way
here, we were driving

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:14.770
and I saw a guy hitchhiking.

00:06:14.770 --> 00:06:15.790
I thought he was
giving me a like.

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:17.040
So it was one of those things.

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:20.722
So it does actually
happen, I guess, here.

00:06:20.722 --> 00:06:22.180
But no, a friend
of mine was trying

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:25.070
to ascertain whether I was
fond of a certain girl.

00:06:25.070 --> 00:06:29.290
And so to distinguish between
liking her as a friend

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:31.930
and like liking her as
someone more than a friend,

00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:35.364
I said to him-- I asked the
question-- "Like like like?"

00:06:35.364 --> 00:06:37.030
That's when I realized
I have a problem.

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:37.530
Ouch.

00:06:37.530 --> 00:06:40.770
You don't want to say "like
like like" three times in a row.

00:06:40.770 --> 00:06:45.920
Anyway, the point being,
that I'm going to talk about

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:48.160
jokes and where you might
find them in society.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:51.880
They appear in different places
and they're more ubiquitous

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:53.000
than you might imagine.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:54.250
There's a dollar word for you.

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.520
You can right-click that one.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:06:59.410
So I'm going to break down
humor, stand-up, jokes,

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:01.650
and lessons from I am Indian.

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:04.229
Let's see how far I get.

00:07:04.229 --> 00:07:05.770
I have a lot of
content here, but I'm

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:07.228
going to treat this
like my dates--

00:07:07.228 --> 00:07:09.527
I'm just going to see
how far I can get.

00:07:09.527 --> 00:07:10.610
That's supposed be a joke.

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:15.330
All right, so let's
start with humor.

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:18.940
The job of a comedian
is to make people laugh.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:21.657
It is the simplest
job in society.

00:07:21.657 --> 00:07:23.490
It's not the easiest,
but it's the simplest.

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:24.590
It's just three words.

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:27.600
If you also want to say
something else, that's great.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:30.240
There are comedians
who say funny things

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:32.430
and there are comedians
who say things funny.

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.390
And they are sort of
two different things

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:37.269
if you have to explain
why a comedian is funny.

00:07:37.269 --> 00:07:39.560
We showed a little clip of
Russell there inadvertently.

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:41.370
But sometimes you may
say, why is he funny.

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:41.920
Ah, I don't know.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:42.587
He's just funny.

00:07:42.587 --> 00:07:43.253
He's just funny.

00:07:43.253 --> 00:07:44.564
The way he is, he's just funny.

00:07:44.564 --> 00:07:45.480
But what does it mean?

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.340
So we've got to break
that down a little bit.

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:51.400
I don't remember if
it was Chris Rock or I

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:58.040
who said this-- I get us mixed
up all the time-- but it was

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:02.950
really-- the goal was to
make people laugh in the room

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:04.147
and think on the way home.

00:08:04.147 --> 00:08:05.230
That was really the thing.

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:06.870
You don't want people to
think while you're here.

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:08.910
Otherwise-- there's no
sound to thinking, right?

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:11.451
So I want you to laugh in the
room and think on the way home.

00:08:11.451 --> 00:08:14.020
That's always a
big thing for us.

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:15.850
And so not all
comedians are what we

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:17.910
would call social commentators.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:20.190
Some people are just
there to get a laugh

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:22.610
and other people want to say
something more than something

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:25.030
funny.

00:08:25.030 --> 00:08:28.351
If we go back to
medieval times, there

00:08:28.351 --> 00:08:29.850
was something called
a court jester.

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:30.660
Round of applause--
how many people

00:08:30.660 --> 00:08:31.590
have heard of a court jester?

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:33.330
How many people have at
least heard of this concept?

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:33.679
OK, that's good.

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:35.780
You can clap, that's
fine-- or raise your hand.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:37.559
Either one is OK.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.862
Does anyone know the
role of the court jester?

00:08:39.862 --> 00:08:42.070
Does anyone know what the
purpose of the court jester

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:42.761
was?

00:08:42.761 --> 00:08:43.261
Yes.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:49.529
Yes, perfect, to point out
the absurdities of society,

00:08:49.529 --> 00:08:50.820
of what's going on around them.

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:53.590
Also, it was to convey
messages to the king

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.280
without fear of being beheaded--
that was a big thing--

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:58.200
without fear of retribution.

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:00.390
That was a really important
message or thing for him

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:04.300
to be able to do, to convey
messages to the king.

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:06.370
Today, we have multiple kings.

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:07.800
We've got the president, sure.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:09.850
The president can
be sort of a king.

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.890
But we also have the media.

00:09:11.890 --> 00:09:14.220
We have the pope-- unless,
again, you're Donald Trump.

00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:16.220
He's going to be a
consistent punch line for me,

00:09:16.220 --> 00:09:19.140
I think, this time-- the pope.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:22.200
We have corporate America
and all of these things

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:23.680
that do exist.

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:27.210
But one by one, through
one scandal or another,

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:30.870
it seems like we've
lost our kings.

00:09:30.870 --> 00:09:35.310
If you go all the way back to
Richard Nixon and Watergate

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:37.020
and the Vietnam
War, the government

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:40.510
lost a lot of credibility
here in this country.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:42.042
And I have to-- in America.

00:09:42.042 --> 00:09:43.250
We have so many Indians here.

00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:45.460
I need to make sure
that we say in America.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:48.580
The government here lost
a lot of credibility.

