00:44:51.802 --> 00:44:53.260
And that was actually
another point

00:44:53.260 --> 00:44:54.770
that-- I'll just go
to my talking points

00:44:54.770 --> 00:44:55.645
like I'm Marco Rubio.

00:44:55.645 --> 00:45:01.106
But you know, Barack Obama
knew exactly what he was doing.

00:45:01.106 --> 00:45:02.230
I'll just keep saying that.

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:04.021
But that's the idea.

00:45:04.021 --> 00:45:06.270
As a commercial, we were
always trying to reach people

00:45:06.270 --> 00:45:07.880
and saying where
are they receptive.

00:45:07.880 --> 00:45:08.860
Should it be a TV ad?

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:09.990
Should be a billboard?

00:45:09.990 --> 00:45:11.580
Should it be an internet pop-up?

00:45:11.580 --> 00:45:13.840
Please God, no.

00:45:13.840 --> 00:45:16.630
And jokes are the same
way, right, where you go,

00:45:16.630 --> 00:45:17.730
does this work as a tweet.

00:45:17.730 --> 00:45:19.271
Does it work as an
Instagram picture?

00:45:19.271 --> 00:45:21.110
Does it work on stage?

00:45:21.110 --> 00:45:23.370
Is it a sketch or
is it a commercial?

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:26.000
So I think part of
being a comedian

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.790
is being able to tell jokes
in a wide variety of media.

00:45:28.790 --> 00:45:30.670
And so a lot of people
ask me that-- so,

00:45:30.670 --> 00:45:32.840
how do you go over in India?

00:45:32.840 --> 00:45:35.400
And I think it works,
I think, largely,

00:45:35.400 --> 00:45:39.710
because I try to talk about
our-- there's an old quote that

00:45:39.710 --> 00:45:44.690
says we bond according
to our similarities

00:45:44.690 --> 00:45:47.100
and we grow according to our
differences, which I think

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:48.680
is beautiful and I love that.

00:45:48.680 --> 00:45:50.679
But I think that
a lot of comedy is

00:45:50.679 --> 00:45:51.970
about bringing people together.

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:53.180
What do we all do together?

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:54.940
And I find that stuff
to be a lot more

00:45:54.940 --> 00:45:56.940
fun than the stuff that
sort of divides us apart

00:45:56.940 --> 00:45:59.315
and go, well, I disagree with
this or disagree with that.

00:45:59.315 --> 00:46:01.740
So I think, in that way, being
able to write commercials

00:46:01.740 --> 00:46:03.948
is kind of cool, because
you get to express something

00:46:03.948 --> 00:46:05.490
in a visual medium.

00:46:05.490 --> 00:46:07.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: How did
you get into comedy?

00:46:07.630 --> 00:46:10.730
Like saying you were a
materials engineer, then

00:46:10.730 --> 00:46:13.030
you worked with
P&amp;G as a marketer--

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:16.120
what was your in into comedy?

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.299
RAJIV SATYAL: I volunteered
at a tennis tournament,

00:46:19.299 --> 00:46:20.090
because I'm Indian.

00:46:20.090 --> 00:46:21.800
And you have to do something
with tennis, right?

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:23.340
It has to-- in this
country, especially.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:24.250
It's cricket in India.

00:46:24.250 --> 00:46:26.280
But here, the Indians who
couldn't play football,

00:46:26.280 --> 00:46:28.154
we basically had to do
something with tennis.

00:46:28.154 --> 00:46:31.130
And so I worked in
the player locker room

00:46:31.130 --> 00:46:33.730
in Cincinnati, which is one
of the-- there are the four

00:46:33.730 --> 00:46:34.870
grand slams in
tennis-- I don't know

00:46:34.870 --> 00:46:37.369
how much everyone knows about
tennis-- the four grand slams.

00:46:37.369 --> 00:46:40.094
And then it's the third
largest tournament after that.

00:46:40.094 --> 00:46:42.260
So it's one of the biggest
tournaments in the world.

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:46.470
And I was working in the locker
room, got to see the players--

00:46:46.470 --> 00:46:48.565
a little bit too
much of the players.

