00:55:53.390 --> 00:55:55.545
But I don't think, any
more, people feel that.

00:55:55.545 --> 00:55:56.920
The first two
years I did comedy,

00:55:56.920 --> 00:55:59.210
I didn't do any Indian
jokes at all-- none.

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:02.270
And so I don't think
it's necessary.

00:56:02.270 --> 00:56:04.569
But I think we can support
Indian American comedians

00:56:04.569 --> 00:56:06.860
and I really appreciate the
support today and everybody

00:56:06.860 --> 00:56:07.360
coming out.

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:12.200
Because this is how we do
it to quote Montell Jordan.

00:56:12.200 --> 00:56:14.360
FEMALE SPEAKER: I would
put in one of my questions.

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:16.744
So you said that you
guys just got married.

00:56:16.744 --> 00:56:18.410
Thank you for coming
here today, Harsha.

00:56:18.410 --> 00:56:21.100
And I know that
there's a funny story

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:22.680
behind how you proposed to her.

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:24.520
Do you want to tell
that story to everyone?

00:56:24.520 --> 00:56:26.705
RAJIV SATYAL: Or do you?

00:56:26.705 --> 00:56:29.080
The way you said it I though
maybe you wanted to tell it,

00:56:29.080 --> 00:56:30.038
so I thought, OK, fine.

00:56:30.038 --> 00:56:34.680
Well, I proposed to Harsha on
stage, which was kind of cool.

00:56:34.680 --> 00:56:37.070
We were-- I was performing
at the Cincinnati Funny Bone.

00:56:37.070 --> 00:56:39.575
And I was opening
for Kevin Nealon,

00:56:39.575 --> 00:56:41.450
who you might know from
"Saturday Night Live"

00:56:41.450 --> 00:56:42.400
or from "Weeds."

00:56:42.400 --> 00:56:44.655
And I proposed to Harsha.

00:56:44.655 --> 00:56:46.280
There's actually a
YouTube video of it,

00:56:46.280 --> 00:56:49.170
so you can Google it or
YouTube it, and look it up,

00:56:49.170 --> 00:56:51.670
and see that proposal,
which is pretty cool.

00:56:51.670 --> 00:56:53.670
And then I did that in
front of Kevin Nealon.

00:56:53.670 --> 00:56:55.920
And then we had Russell
Peters perform at our wedding.

00:56:55.920 --> 00:56:57.080
So that was pretty sweet.

00:56:57.080 --> 00:57:00.640
That was a great comedic
arc to the whole thing.

00:57:00.640 --> 00:57:02.570
And since I had to be
the last one to speak,

00:57:02.570 --> 00:57:04.445
I could say Russell
Peters has opened for me,

00:57:04.445 --> 00:57:05.740
so that was the whole idea.

00:57:05.740 --> 00:57:07.880
But we got married--
Harsha is from Austin,

00:57:07.880 --> 00:57:09.280
so we got married in Texas.

00:57:09.280 --> 00:57:13.000
And we had a full-on
cowboys and Indians wedding,

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:15.340
because it was kind of great.

00:57:15.340 --> 00:57:17.990
Because we're Indians,
but I'm a cowboy.

00:57:17.990 --> 00:57:18.500
I'm Hindu.

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:19.300
I worship cows.

00:57:19.300 --> 00:57:20.690
So I really am a cowboy.

00:57:23.620 --> 00:57:24.870
FEMALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:57:24.870 --> 00:57:27.953
We have time for one more
question from the audience.

00:57:31.970 --> 00:57:33.220
RAJIV SATYAL: We exhausted it.

00:57:33.220 --> 00:57:34.886
It's like popcorn
that stopping popping.

00:57:34.886 --> 00:57:35.986
Rania.

00:57:35.986 --> 00:57:37.969
AUDIENCE: So in terms
of asking-- sorry,

00:57:37.969 --> 00:57:40.468
in terms of making jokes that,
sometimes, can offend people,

00:57:40.468 --> 00:57:42.958
I'm just curious about
any time that, maybe, you

00:57:42.958 --> 00:57:45.448
have made a joke that crossed
the line, how you recovered.

00:57:47.950 --> 00:57:50.320
RAJIV SATYAL: I mean,
I've bombed many times.

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:52.140
I mean, every comedian has.

00:57:52.140 --> 00:57:53.680
But I'm trying to
think if I've done

00:57:53.680 --> 00:57:59.061
anything that was so over
the top that really offended

00:57:59.061 --> 00:57:59.560
people.

00:57:59.560 --> 00:58:01.560
I mean, I've definitely
had people come up to me

00:58:01.560 --> 00:58:05.040
after shows and say, wow,
that was-- that one joke.

00:58:05.040 --> 00:58:07.750
Actually, there was a
joke I did-- OK, yeah.

00:58:07.750 --> 00:58:11.130
So I was in Chicago and I was
performing with Hari Kondabolu.

00:58:11.130 --> 00:58:12.720
Hannibal Buress,
actually, was there.

00:58:12.720 --> 00:58:13.970
Hannibal Buress
was our headliner.

00:58:13.970 --> 00:58:15.600
It was all mostly
a Desi comedy show.

00:58:15.600 --> 00:58:17.183
It was an Indian
comedy show, largely.

00:58:17.183 --> 00:58:19.920
But we had Hannibal Buress
perform, actually, in Chicago.

00:58:19.920 --> 00:58:24.170
And it was for a
women's shelter.

00:58:24.170 --> 00:58:24.810
OK?

00:58:24.810 --> 00:58:28.510
So I did one of my jokes that
I do that usually goes over

00:58:28.510 --> 00:58:29.110
really well.

00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:30.859
And it didn't in the
beginning, because it

00:58:30.859 --> 00:58:32.860
had a certain-- I
did the joke where

00:58:32.860 --> 00:58:35.850
I go, we all have a number
on a scale from one to 10.

00:58:35.850 --> 00:58:38.090
And I'm a 6, and I know
that, and that's fine.

00:58:38.090 --> 00:58:40.173
And she's looking at me
like, dude, you're a four.

00:58:40.173 --> 00:58:42.102
But seriously, the idea
is-- the thing is--

00:58:42.102 --> 00:58:44.060
and I'm Indian, so I've
come up with a formula.

00:58:44.060 --> 00:58:46.082
And the formula is,
you can only date

00:58:46.082 --> 00:58:48.040
and be happy with somebody
who's up or down one

00:58:48.040 --> 00:58:49.300
digit from you on the scale.

00:58:49.300 --> 00:58:49.800
OK?

00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:50.430
That's-- really, it is.

00:58:50.430 --> 00:58:52.380
So if you're a six, you can
be happy with a five, six,

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:52.680
or seven.

00:58:52.680 --> 00:58:53.105
Don't act.

00:58:53.105 --> 00:58:53.890
Ask how this happened.

00:58:53.890 --> 00:58:54.431
I don't know.

00:58:54.431 --> 00:58:56.667
But that's the rule, right?

00:58:56.667 --> 00:58:58.250
So you can date a
five, six, or seven.

00:58:58.250 --> 00:59:00.010
But I married a 10.

00:59:00.010 --> 00:59:02.750
So at the time, I was single.

00:59:02.750 --> 00:59:04.780
And so I said, but
I've dated tens before.

00:59:04.780 --> 00:59:06.310
And people go,
well, how is that.

00:59:06.310 --> 00:59:08.310
Well, the thing is, women,
you are what you are.

00:59:08.310 --> 00:59:10.520
I go, you know, if you're
an eight, you're an eight.

00:59:10.520 --> 00:59:11.080
You're beautiful.

00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:12.660
But you can't go up
or down on the scale.

00:59:12.660 --> 00:59:13.993
We live in a chauvinist society.

00:59:13.993 --> 00:59:16.250
But fellas can go up on
the scale if we're funny

00:59:16.250 --> 00:59:17.460
and we have money.

00:59:17.460 --> 00:59:19.279
So I'm a six for looks.

00:59:19.279 --> 00:59:20.320
I'm funny on most nights.

00:59:20.320 --> 00:59:21.090
I become a seven.

00:59:21.090 --> 00:59:23.298
I've got some money in the
bank so i become an eight.

00:59:23.298 --> 00:59:24.440
And that's how I date tens.

00:59:24.440 --> 00:59:25.680
And I know some people are
looking at me, like, yeah,

00:59:25.680 --> 00:59:27.820
but that's still
two numbers apart.

00:59:27.820 --> 00:59:28.320
Right?

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:30.890
What I do is I meet at 10 and
I break her self-esteem down

00:59:30.890 --> 00:59:32.296
so she thinks she's a nine.

00:59:32.296 --> 00:59:33.030
Right?

00:59:33.030 --> 00:59:33.655
It's funny.

00:59:33.655 --> 00:59:34.155
See?

00:59:34.155 --> 00:59:35.350
Everybody's laughing.

00:59:35.350 --> 00:59:39.170
But the room, being a battered
women's shelter kind of

00:59:39.170 --> 00:59:42.770
went-- you know, one
of those moments.

00:59:42.770 --> 00:59:44.950
And Hari comes back to me
backstage and just goes,

00:59:44.950 --> 00:59:47.770
dude, telling that
joke at this place.

00:59:47.770 --> 00:59:48.454
I go, I know.

00:59:48.454 --> 00:59:51.120
And I had a couple women come up
to me and say, come on, really.

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:52.760
I said, yeah, it's funny.

00:59:52.760 --> 00:59:54.530
I mean, sorry, that's
a funny joke, OK?

00:59:54.530 --> 00:59:55.550
It's just funny.

00:59:55.550 --> 00:59:57.330
But yeah, I think
that was definitely

00:59:57.330 --> 00:59:58.560
not knowing your audience.

00:59:58.560 --> 01:00:00.643
And I didn't get to that
part of the presentation,

01:00:00.643 --> 01:00:03.000
but I do a whole thing
about knowing your audience.

